\begin_layout Standard
Now 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{2}
q & =\int i\d{t}\\
\therefore V_{c} & =\frac{\int i\d{t}}{C} & \qquad\text{\noun{Or}}\qquad\dx{V_{c}}{t} & =\frac{i}{C}\\
 &  & \qquad i & =C\dx{V_{c}}{t}
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset

 When 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{c}$
\end_inset

 is constant, 
\begin_inset Formula $i=0$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, there is no current flows through a capacitor when a dc voltage
 is applied.
 Therefore, under dc conditions, the capacitor acts as an open circuit.
 But current does flow through a capacitor when the applied voltage across
 it changes, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\because i & =C\dx{V_{c}}{t}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 When 
\begin_inset Formula $\dx{V_{c}}{t}$
\end_inset

 is large, the current is large.
 For an infinitesimally small time interval, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta V$
\end_inset

 will be very small as well, but the ratio of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\Delta V}{\Delta t}$
\end_inset

 may be significant.
 This implies then that the current, 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 may be appreciable.
 But as usual, the effective resistance, 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\frac{\Delta V}{\Delta i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the infinitesimal changes, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta V$
\end_inset

 may be small and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta i$
\end_inset

 may be large, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $R\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore a capacitor will act as a short circuit when instantaneous changes
 occur.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
