\begin_layout Standard
If the current is constant, then 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{L}=0$
\end_inset

.
 If the current changes, the magnetic field changes as well,so, by Faraday's
 Law, there is an induced electromotive force (back emf), 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\epsilon & =-\dx{\phi}{t}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is the flux threading the coil.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\propto i$
\end_inset

, which means 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\phi & =Li\\
\therefore\epsilon & =-L\dx{i}{t}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $i=$
\end_inset

 constant, then 
\begin_inset Formula $V=0$
\end_inset

.
 So the inductor acts as a short circuit under dc conditions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For infinitesimally small changes, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 will be small and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta i$
\end_inset

 will be small also.
 But again, the ratio, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\Delta t}{\Delta i}$
\end_inset

, may be significant, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta L$
\end_inset

 may be significant.
 The effective resistance is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
R & =\frac{\Delta V}{\Delta i}\\
 & \approx\frac{\text{finite}}{\text{zero}}\rightarrow\infty
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 Therefore for instantaneous changes, the inductor behaves like an open
 circuit.
 
\end_layout

